10.2: Color channel statistics

Adrian

In our previous lesson, we learned about three important terms in computer vision: image descriptors, feature descriptors, and feature vectors.

As a quick recap, feature vectors are a list of numbers used quantify and abstractly quantify images. These feature vectors can then be compared using distance functions/similarity metrics to determine how “similar” two images are. Feature vectors are also used as inputs to machine learning models that can be trained to recognize the contents of an image.

In order to extract feature vectors from images, we utilize image descriptors and feature descriptors. In computer vision literature the two terms can be used almost interchangeably, and the only way to disambiguate between them is based on the context of the author. However, there is an important difference.

Image descriptors are extracted globally from an image, implying that for one input image, we get one feature vector out.

Feature descriptors, on the other hand, describe the salient or interesting regions of an image — this means that for one input image, we can get multiple feature vectors out.

We’ll be continuing our discussion of image descriptors and feature descriptors throughout the rest of this module, but today we are going to look at an example of arguably the most basic image descriptor — color channel statistics.

Objectives:

This lesson has two objectives:

  1. Learn how to extract color channel statistic feature vectors from images.
  2. Apply color channel statistics and the Euclidean distance to rank images for similarity.

Color Channel Statistics

Perhaps this is my personal opinion being injected into the course, but I would absolutely argue that color channel statistics are the easiest and most intuitive image descriptors to understand. By computing basic statistics, such as mean and standard deviation for each channel of an image, we are able to quantify and represent the color distribution of an image. Therefore, if two images have similar means and standard deviations, we can assume that these images have similar color distributions:

Figure 1: Based on the color distributions, the top two images are more similar than the bottom two.

Note: Comparing images based on their color distributions is almost as old as the computer vision field itself. When used in practice, we assume that images that have similar color distributions also have similar visual contents. This is clearly not always possible, as a white horse in a green field will have a similar color distribution as a white monkey in the rainforest. However, it’s a nice assumption to make when using small datasets and can lead to decent results.

Color statistics are often not as powerful as histograms, but they are also more compact. As I mentioned, they are one of the easiest and most basic image descriptors, so they are an excellent starting point for us.

The color channel image descriptor can be broken down into three steps:

  • Step 1: Separate the input image into its respective channels. For an RGB image, we want to examine each of the Red, Green, and Blue channels independently.
  • Step 2: Compute various statistics for each channel, such as mean, standard deviation, skew, and kurtosis.
  • Step 3: Concatenate the statistics together to form a “list” of statistics for each color channel — this becomes our feature vector.

For example, given an input RGB image, our pipeline would look like this:

Figure 2: The pipeline of our color channel statistics image descriptor. We start with an input image, apply the image descriptor, and left with the mean and standard deviation of each channel of the input image.

On the left we have our input image that we want to extract color channel statistics from. In the middle is our image descriptor — this box governs how we extract the color channel statistics. And finally on the right we have our output feature vector which consists of the mean and standard deviation for each of the Red, Green, and Blue channels, respectively.

Since this is our first image descriptor, the best way to explain extracting color channel statistics is with an example, hands-on code.

First, we need a dataset of images to extract features from:

Figure 3: Our dataset of four images that we’ll be comparing for similarity. Notice how three of the images have similar color distributions, while the third image is clearly an outlier.

In the above image, we have four screen captures from my favorite movie, Jurassic Park. In each of the four screen captures we have the menacing T-Rex.

If you’ve ever seen Jurassic Park before you’ll know that trex_01.png , trex_02.png , and trex_04.png  all occur during the middle of the movie, when the power systems fail and the dinosaurs are able to stomp around the park at free will. The final image, trex_03.png , is toward the end of the movie.

Looking at these images, we see that trex_01.png , trex_02.png , and trex_04.png  all have similar dark colors due to it being dark, outside, and during thunderstorm. Conversely, trex_03.png  appears to be captured during the daytime, inside, with lots of natural light.

Intuitively your brain is able to see that trex_01.png , trex_02.png , and trex_04.png  are all very similar to each other, while trex_03.png  is clearly the outlier.

But how do we use color channel statistics to programmatically determine this?

I’m glad you asked. Open up a new file, name it color_channel_stats.py , and insert the following code:

color_channel_stats.py

# import the necessary packages
from scipy.spatial import distance as dist
from imutils import paths
import numpy as np
import cv2
 
# grab the list of image paths and initialize the index to store the image filename
# and feature vector
imagePaths = sorted(list(paths.list_images("dinos")))
index = {}
 
# loop over the image paths
for imagePath in imagePaths:
# load the image and extract the filename
image = cv2.imread(imagePath)
filename = imagePath[imagePath.rfind("/") + 1:]
 
# extract the mean and standard deviation from each channel of the
# BGR image, then update the index with the feature vector
(means, stds) = cv2.meanStdDev(image)
features = np.concatenate([means, stds]).flatten()
index[filename] = features

Lines 2-5 import our required packages, which should start to feel pretty standard by now. However, there is the exception of the SciPy’s distance  sub-module. What in the world is that?

Well, the distance  sub-module of SciPy contains many distance metrics and similarity functions that we can use to compute the distance/similarity between two feature vectors. In this particular example we’ll be using the Euclidean distance, which is pretty much the de facto standard when it comes to computing the distance between two points in a Euclidean space.

You are likely already familiar with the Euclidean distance and have probably used it in middle school and high school Algebra and Geometry, but let’s define it anyway. Given two input vectors, and :

As you can see, the Euclidean distance simply takes the sum of squared difference between each entry in the  and vectors, and finally takes the square-root of this sum.

A larger Euclidean distance implies that the two points are farther away from each other in a Euclidean space. A smaller Euclidean distance implies that the two points are closer together in a Euclidean space, with a distance of 0 implying that the points are identical.

Later in this example, we’ll be using the Euclidean distance to compare our color channel feature vectors for similarity.

Anyway, now that we have our packages imported we can move on to Lines 9 and 10:

  • Line 9 simply grabs the (sorted) list of image paths from our dinos  directory. The dinos  directory contains the four images of the T-Rex we are going to extract color channel feature vectors from.
  • Line 10 defines a Python dictionary (basically a Hash Table, if you’re more familiar with that data structure) called index . It’s very common to use dictionaries/Hash Tables when extracting features from images. This is because each input image is unique; therefore, we can use a unique key (such as the filename or UUID) as the key to our dictionary. As for the value of the dictionary, that will simply be our feature vector. Again, by using a dictionary data structure we are able to use the (unique) image filename as the key and the feature vector extracted from the image as the value.

Moving on, extracting our color channel feature vectors take place on Lines 13-22.

We start looping over our T-Rex images on Line 13, followed by loading the image from disk and extracting the filename from the image path on Lines 15 and 16.

To compute the mean and standard deviation for each channel in the image, we’ll utilize the cv2.meanStdDev  function on Line 20. This function accepts a single parameter, our image , and then computes the mean and standard deviation for each channel in the image. In our case, the cv2.meanStdDev  function will take our input image and compute the mean and standard deviation for each of the Red, Green, and Blue channels, respectively.

Now that we have the means and standard deviations for each channel, we need to concatenate them all together to form our feature vector (Line 21). Remember, a feature vector is just a list of numbers used to quantify the contents of an image. In this case, our feature vector consists of the means and standard deviations, allowing us to characterize the color distribution of our images.

Finally, we take the unique filename  and our features  and store them in our index  dictionary so we can compare them for similarity.

The actual comparison for similarity takes place below:

# display the query image and grab the sorted keys of the index dictionary
query = cv2.imread(imagePaths[0])
cv2.imshow("Query (trex_01.png)", query)
keys = sorted(index.keys())
 
# loop over the filenames in the dictionary
for (i, k) in enumerate(keys):
# if this is the first image, ignore it
if k == "trex_01.png":
continue
 
# load the current image and compute the Euclidean distance between the
# query image (i.e. the 1st image) and the current image
image = cv2.imread(imagePaths[i])
d = dist.euclidean(index["trex_01.png"], index[k])
 
# display the distance between the query image and the current image
cv2.putText(image, "%.2f" % (d), (10, 30), cv2.FONT_HERSHEY_SIMPLEX, 0.75, (0, 255, 0), 2)
cv2.imshow(k, image)
 
# wait for a keypress
cv2.waitKey(0)

When comparing images (or building image search engines), it’s common to have this notion of a query.

Think back to the last time you went to Google and ran a search. You inputted a set of keywords — maybe you searched for “pyimagesearch blog.” Google then took these keywords, called a query, and used them to rank all the webpages online, giving you back the most relevant result.

We apply the same process in the code segment above, only using images rather than text. As you can see from Lines 25 and 26, we’ll be using the trex_01.png  image as our query image — all other images in our dataset, (i.e. trex_02.png , trex_03.png , and trex_04.png ) will be compared to trex_01.png .

We start the actual comparison and ranking process on Lines 30-33, where we loop over each of the filenames and associated feature vectors in the index  dictionary. If the current image in the loop is our query image, we simply ignore it and continue looping. Comparing a query image to itself is not very interesting — it will be 100% identical to itself.

The most interesting line to pay attention to here is Line 38. Here we use the dist.euclidean  function to compute the Euclidean distance between the query image feature vector and the feature vectors in our dataset. As I mentioned above, similar images will have a smaller Euclidean distance, whereas less similar images will have a larger Euclidean distance.

Finally, Lines 41-45 wrap up our example by writing the Euclidean distance on the image and showing our output.

To see our color channel statistics in action, just execute the following command:

color_channel_stats.py
Python
1
$ python color_channel_stats.py

Figure 4: The output of comparing the top-left image to the other 3 images in our dataset for similarity. Notice how the images of the T-Rex captured during the same scene of Jurassic Park are more similar to each other than the bottom-right screen capture at the end of the movie.

On the top-left we have our query image, trex_01.png . Notice how the distance between the feature vectors associated with trex_01.png  and trex_02.png  is quite small. The same goes for the distance between trex_01.png  and trex_04.png . However, when we look at the Euclidean distance between the color channel feature vectors for trex_01.png  and trex_03.png , we see that the distance substantially larger than the previous images.

Why is this?

Because the color distributions are much different, of course!

The three screen captures of the T-Rex taken at night, in the jungle, in a downpour have much more similar color distributions than the image on the bottom-right, which was clearly captured during the day, inside, with an abundance of natural light.

By using basic color channel statistics we were able to correctly rank the images in terms of their similarity.

Summary:

This lesson allowed us to get our hands dirty with the most basic image descriptor — color channel statistics.

We computed the mean and standard deviation of each Red, Green, and Blue channel of our input image, concatenated these means and standard deviations together, and used this list of statistics as our feature vector.

From there, we utilized the Euclidean distance to compare images for similarity. Images with smaller distances lie closer together in the Euclidean space and are considered more similar. Images with larger distances are therefore considered less similar.

If you’re feeling a little shaky extracting features and comparing them, no worries — we’ll be doing comparing feature vectors and ranking images throughout the rest of this course, especially when we get to the Content-Based Image Retrieval module where I’ll dive much, much deeper into the distance metrics and similarity metrics. In the meantime, I suggest reading through the PyImageSearch blog post on building a basic image search engine — this post will help solidify the concept of extracting feature vectors from images, comparing them, and ranking images based on their similarity.

Next up, we’ll dive into another basic, yet very powerful image descriptor, the color histogram, and use it “cluster” images together into groups based on their visual contents.
